definition.value: A phosphate-linked oligosaccharide analogue consisting of two N-acetyl-alpha-D-mannosamine units joined by a (1->6)-phosphodiester linkage.
An organic phosphate consisting of an oligosaccharide analogue having its individual sugar components joined by phosphate rather than glycosidic linkages.

A member of the class of phenylureas that is urea in which one of the nitrogens bears a 3-tert-butyl-1-[(3S)-3-carboxy-1,2,3,4-tetrahydroisoquinolin-6-yl]-1H-pyrazol-5-yl substituent, while the other bears a 2,3-dichlorophenyl group.
A phosphate-linked oligosaccharide analogue consisting of three N-acetyl-alpha-D-mannosamine units joined by (1->6)-phosphodiester linkages.
A polysaccharide composed of a backbone of repeating alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->3)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl units, joined by (1->3)-linkages

A branched polysaccharide composed of a backbone of repeating alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->3)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-[alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->3)]-alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl units, joined by (1->3)-linkages.

A branched polysaccharide derivative composed of a backbone of repeating N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->3)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl units, joined by (1->3)-linkages, as shown.
A branched polysaccharide composed of a backbone of repeating alpha-D-Rhap-(1->3)-[beta-D-Fucf-(1->4)]-alpha-D-Rhap-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap units, joined by (1->3)-linkages as shown.
A polysaccharide composed of a backbone of repeating alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->3)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-rhamnosyl units, joined by (1->3)-linkages.
A branched polysaccharide composed of a backbone of repeating alpha-D-Rhap-(1->3)-[beta-D-Fucf-(1->4)]-alpha-D-Rhap-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap units, joined by (1->3)-linkages as shown.
An amino disaccharide consisting of N-acetyl-D-glucosamine having an alpha-L-fucosyl residue attached at the 3-position.
An amino disaccharide consisting of alpha-L-rhamnopyranose having a beta-anthropyranosyl residue attached at the 3-position.
An amino monosaccharide consisting of D-glucose having a 3-hydroxy-3-methylbutanamido group at the 4-position, a 2-O-methyl group and lacking the 6-hydroxy group.

An amino trisaccharide that consists of a galactopyranose residue attached by a beta-(1->4)-linkage to an N-acetylglucosamine residue, that is in turn attached to a second galactopyranose by a beta-(1->6)-linkage.

An amino tetrasaccharide in which a galactose residue is linked beta(1->3) to the residue at the reducing end of a linear chain of one galactose residue, one  N-acetylglucosamine residue and one N-acetylgalactosamine residue, sequentially linked beta(1->4) and beta(1->6).
An amino trisaccharide that consists of a galactopyranose residue attached by a beta-(1->4)-linkage to an N-acetylglucosamine residue, that is in turn attached to a mannopyranose by a (1->6)-linkage.

An amino pentasaccharide in which a galactose residue is linked beta(1->3) to the residue at the reducing end of a linear chain of two galactose residues, one N-acetylglucosamine residue and one N-acetylgalactosamine residue, sequentially linked alpha(1->4), beta(1->4) and beta(1->6).
An amino pentasaccharide consisting of two units of beta-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->4)-N-acetamido-beta-D-glucosamine, attached by (1->3)- and (1->6)-linkages to a D-galactopyranose.
A glucosaminyl group derived from alpha-L-Fuc-(1->3)-beta-D-GalNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc.
An N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl group having beta-configuration at its point of attachment and an N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl residue attached at the 4-position via a beta-linkage.
A linear hexasaccharide consisting of D-mannosyl residues connected sequentially by beta-(1->2)-, beta-(1->2)-, alpha-(1->3)-, alpha-(1->2)- and alpha-(1->2)-linkages.
A prenyl- or polyprenyl-hydroquinone that results from the reduction of a plastoquinone to the corresponding hydroquinone.
A sulfoxide that is the S-oxide of biotin.
A 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA where the S-acyl group is specified as (S)-carnitinyl.
A 3-[(5R,6S)-5,6-dihydroxycyclohexa-1,3-dienyl]acrylic acid where the acrylic double bond has (E)-configuration.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion arising from deprotonation of one or more oxoacid OH groups of any polysaccharide acid.
An S-farnesyl-L-cysteine where the C=C double bonds at the 2- and 6-positions both have (E)-configuration.
A lipid A where the free primary hydroxy group of lipid A has a branched decasaccharide attached.
A lipid A where the free primary hydroxy group of lipid A has a branched nonasaccharide attached.
A lipid A where the free primary hydroxy group of lipid A has a branched octasaccharide attached.
A lipid A where the free primary hydroxy group of lipid A has a branched heptasaccharide attached.
A lipid A where the free primary hydroxy group of lipid A has a branched hexasaccharide attached.
A lipid A where the free primary hydroxy group of lipid A has a branched hexasaccharide attached.
An alkyl sulfide consisting of coenzyme A carrying an S-alkyl substituent.
A monomethylxanthine having the methyl group located at the 3-position. It is a metabolite of caffeine.
A methylxanthine carrying a single methyl substituent at any position.
A 3-methylxanthine tautomer where the imidazole proton is located at the 9-position.
A 3-methylxanthine tautomer where the imidazole proton is located at the 7-position.
An organophosphate oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of CoA-disulfide; major species at pH 7.3.
A pyrrolecarboxylate that is the conjugate base of 5-hydroxypyrrole-2-carboxylic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-butynoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A pyrrolecarboxylic acid having the carboxy group at the 2-position as well as a hydroxy group at the 5-position.
A 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate(2-) having D-configuration.
An ammonium ion that is the conjugate base of 5-hydroxykynurenamine, arising from selective protonation of the primary alkylamino function; major species at pH 7.3.
A class of secondary metabolites developed by many plants to influence the behaviour, growth or survival of herbivores, and thus acting as a defence against herbivory.
A phenazine carrying a hydroxy substituent at the 1-position.
A 23,24-dihydrocucurbitacin in which a lanostane skeleton is multi-substituted with hydroxy, methyl and oxo substituents, with unsaturation at position 5; a hydroxy function at C-25 is acetylated.
A 23,24-dihydrocucurbitacin in which a lanostane skeleton is multi-substituted with hydroxy, methyl and oxo substituents, with unsaturation at position 5.
A quinolone consisting of quinolin-4(1H)-one carrying a heptyl substituent at position 2.
